{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534686"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:49:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:49:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15157"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15157"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.43,0.1,0.09,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7845"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116308"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7845"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15157"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98304"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3637"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19116"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41078"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49918"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116308"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with a five-day history of constant fever, severe muscle aches, and headache. She returned from a safari holiday in rural Kenya 5 days ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She did not take any preventative medications nor receive travel immunisations prior to travel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. She has marked scleral icterus and generalised jaundice. There are scattered petechiae on her trunk and arms, with several large ecchymoses on her legs. Her abdomen is tender in the right upper quadrant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal: Haemoglobin 132 g/L (115-165), Platelets 45 x 10^9/L (150-400), Total bilirubin 85 \u03bcmol/L (3-20), ALT 850 U/L (5-40), AST 920 U/L (5-40), INR 2.8 (0.9-1.2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Viral hepatitis A","Yellow fever","Zika","Leptospirosis","Malaria"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a severe febrile illness characterised by jaundice, bleeding manifestations, and liver dysfunction following travel to an endemic area. The diagnosis of yellow fever is supported by the characteristic progression, severe liver dysfunction, coagulopathy, and appropriate travel history to an endemic area without vaccination 3 - 6 days ago (the incubation period). The presence of jaundice, petechiae, and ecchymoses are typical dermatological findings in severe cases. This is likely to be Yellow Fever, and the patient should have nucleic acid amplification testing (RT-PCR) testing and IgM serology for confirmation though they may be negative after the first week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYellow fever\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as a biphasic illness with an initial \u0027red phase\u0027 of fever, myalgia, and headache, followed by a brief period of improvement. Some patients then progress to the toxic \u0027yellow phase\u0027 characterised by returning fever, jaundice, bleeding manifestations, and multi-organ dysfunction after the initial 48 hours. It is a flavivirus transmitted by mosquitoes endemic in Africa, Caribbean and South America. Though treatment is only supportive, it is an important notifiable diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral hepatitis A\u003C/strong\u003E can cause similar liver dysfunction and jaundice but typically has a more gradual onset and does not cause the severe bleeding manifestations seen here. The marked coagulopathy and petechiae would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZika\u003C/strong\u003E virus infection typically presents with mild symptoms including fever, rash, conjunctivitis, muscle and joint pain, and headache. Severe manifestations with jaundice, significant liver dysfunction, and coagulopathy as seen in this patient would be highly unusual for Zika infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeptospirosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with fever, myalgia, and jaundice (Weil\u0027s disease). However, the bleeding manifestations are typically less severe, and conjunctival suffusion rather than icterus would be more characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalaria\u003C/strong\u003E can present with fever and thrombocytopenia, but jaundice and bleeding manifestations of this severity would be unusual. The pattern of fever would depend on the type of Plasmodium parasite and tend to be tertian (every other day) or quartan (every third day) and are manifest by clear bouts of chills, high fever and sweating. These of not the features of this patient\u0027s illness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Yellow fever presents with a biphasic illness including an initial \u0027red phase\u0027 of fever and myalgia followed by a \u0027yellow phase\u0027 with jaundice and bleeding.","Dermatological findings in severe yellow fever include jaundice, petechiae, and ecchymoses.","Yellow fever is a flavivirus endemic in parts of Africa and South America requiring vaccination for prevention."],"references":["Clinical Features and Diagnosis of Yellow Fever.  Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. 2024.  Available at: https://www.cdc.gov/yellow-fever/hcp/clinical-diagnosis/index.html#:~:text=Laboratory%20diagnosis%20of%20yellow%20fever,Ig)%20M%20and%20neutralizing%20antibodies.","Domingo C, Charrel RN, Schmidt-Chanasit J, Zeller H, Reusken C. Yellow fever in the diagnostics laboratory. Emerg Microbes Infect. 2018 Jul 12;7(1).  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6043483/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98304"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15157"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98304"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T11:11:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T11:12:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7845"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116308"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tag